player.seasonOutlook: Move over, Clayton Kershaw, it's Scherzer's game now. Scherzer has been a model of durability and consistency for nearly a decade now, and in the past six seasons alone, he has finished among the top five in his league's Cy Young balloting each year while winning three times, and he has been the No. 1 or 2 starting pitcher in rotisserie leagues four times. During that same time (2013-18), he has 11 more wins, 11 more quality starts and 134 more strikeouts than any other pitcher, and his 2.81 ERA and 0.97 WHIP rank third and second (among pitchers with at least 600 innings pitched). What's more, Scherzer raised the bar in terms of strikeouts last season, reaching the 300-K plateau to become only the 14th pitcher to strike out at least that many during the expansion era (since 1961). If there are any concerns about his future, it's that he's 34 and one of the bigger fly ball pitchers in the game, putting him at risk of costly home runs. With no sign of Scherzer slipping, though, he's almost indisputably the No. 1 pitcher in any league format, and there's a compelling case for him to be the first pick overall in a points-based league.

Only a persistent bout with shoulder inflammation during the second half of last season served as an obstacle to Sale challenging for the honor of No. 1 pitcher in fantasy, and that he managed to finish 18th on the Player Rater and 12th in terms of fantasy points despite pitching only 158 innings is a testament to his otherworldly skills. He managed at least a 30 percent strikeout rate for the fourth time, his walk rate was under 6 percent for a sixth consecutive season, and he surrendered hard contact (per Statcast) on only 27 percent of his balls in play, fourth best among pitchers with at least 25 starts. In short, Sale showed little to no sign of loss of skill due to the ailment, with a roughly 1.5 mph drop in average fastball velocity being the most noticeable effect. That does make him a pitcher more worth tracking, health-wise, during spring training than the others ranked in his range, but it's not enough to drop him from the top three among starters in any fantasy format.

No pitcher in the history of baseball has experienced a more dominating season that failed to result in bushels of wins for his real-life team than deGrom, and as a testament to how much the game has progressed, he won the National League's Cy Young Award (and nearly unanimously at that) despite totaling 10 wins. Among deGrom's feats: He led the majors in ERA (1.70), quality starts (28, tied) and FIP (1.99), and he finished in the top four in WHIP, WAR, K's and batting average allowed. He also set a single-year record with 24 consecutive quality starts. Further illustrating the folly of the "win": deGrom's 19 quality starts that failed to result in an individual win set a single-season record, and bear in mind that he pitched at least seven innings in 15 of those, demonstrating how unusually unlucky he was. For his encore, deGrom might not enjoy quite so much good fortune in terms of BABIP (.283 in 2018, 13 points beneath his career mark), left-on-base percentage (82.0, more than three percentage points beneath his career rate) or home run/fly ball percentage (6.0, nearly three percentage points beneath his career number), so his ERA and WHIP are sure to increase slightly. His surging swinging-strike rate supports his candidacy as one of the top pitchers in baseball (and fantasy baseball), and he's sure to be even slightly more fortunate in the win column, considering his New York Mets should be more competitive.

Kluber has been one of the most consistently productive starting pitchers in baseball during the past half-decade. His 83 wins and 114 quality starts since the beginning of the 2014 season rank second in the majors, his 1,228 strikeouts rank third, and his 2.85 ERA and 1.02 WHIP rank fourth (minimum 500 innings pitched during that time). Only a knee injury -- one that never actually required a disabled-list stint, by the way -- served as a blemish on his 2018, with the most significant concern the drop of his season-long strikeout rate to 26.4 percent, his lowest since 2013, which was much lower during his initial few starts after the issue surfaced in mid-July. Kluber did recover with a handful of dominant late-season starts, which bolsters his candidacy for a top-three pick among starting pitchers in any fantasy format and for a third career American League Cy Young Award. He's one of the few pitchers worth being one of the building-block, top-25-overall draft selections in a rotisserie league, and he should be one of the first dozen or so players off the board in points-based formats.

Nola's big league career has followed a stepladder pattern through four years, but his ability to stay healthy enough to total career bests in starts (33) and innings (212 1/3) in 2018 was the most significant development of all. To the health point, Nola has enjoyed an uptick in velocity on all of his pitches in each of the past two seasons, averaging a career-high 93.5 mph with his four-seam fastball specifically. That's largely why he's so good at minimizing hard contact. And the fact that he was the only pitcher in baseball last season to post at least a 50 percent ground ball rate and 25 percent strikeout rate with no greater than a 7.5 percent walk rate shows how low-risk his skill set is. Nola did enjoy some good fortune on balls in play and stranding runners, so expect some regression in ERA/WHIP, but he's still one of the highest-floor pitchers available in any fantasy format. Maybe he doesn't feel like a building-block starter based on his age and experience level, but he's earned that status.

OK, we simply cannot ignore Kershaw's injury history at this point, and it's now significant enough that it's almost impossible to make the case for him being the first pitcher picked in a fantasy baseball draft. Kershaw has averaged 27 starts and 183 1/3 innings during the past five seasons, has made five disabled-list trips during that time, and has missed 28.5 percent of the Los Angeles Dodgers' schedule while on the DL in the past three seasons alone. What's more, while prior to 2018 he had provided undeniably-best-in-the-game statistics in his healthy stints, there were hints of slight skills erosion last year: His average fastball velocity dipped to a career-low 91.3 mph (he ranged from 93-94 mph in the previous three years) and opponents batted .299/.335/.509 with a .367 wOBA against the pitch (all career-worst rates), forcing him to rely much more heavily on his slider. The result was a 23.9 percent overall strikeout rate for the season that was his lowest since his 2008 rookie campaign. Kershaw nevertheless dominated while healthy for the Dodgers' final 81 team games, going 15-for-16 in quality starts with a 2.67 ERA and 0.99 WHIP, guaranteeing him a top-10 finish in any fantasy format if he tallies the requisite innings. There are more durable alternatives in that tier these days, though.

Verlander's trade to Houston was a blessing, as he has been a perfect fit in the Astros' underrated-for-pitchers home venue as well as with their coaching staff, whose video analysis has helped him polish his changeup and slider. Since that Aug. 31, 2017, deal, Verlander's 21 wins is tied for sixth in the majors, his 31 quality starts ranks second, 2.32 ERA is fourth, 0.87 WHIP first and 333 strikeouts second. What's more, he has a 2.83 postseason ERA in nine appearances during that same span (which are not accounted for in those rankings). Verlander, 36 when the 2019 season opens, has shown no sign of slowing down, though at this career stage it's probably wise to account for some slight ERA/WHIP regression considering he enjoyed a career-best (by far) 85.3 left-on-base percentage and is one of the game's most extreme fly ball pitchers (31.7 percent, second-highest among ERA qualifiers). Sum it up and he's still a top-eight pitcher regardless of league format.

Not every pitcher is worse off with a move from the National to American Leagues. Presenting Cole, who ditched his slider in favor of more four-seam fastballs upon his move to Houston, resulting in his obliterating his previous pro-career best with a 34.5 percent strikeout rate at the expense of a near-10-percent drop in his ground ball rate. Considering his elite velocity -- he averaged a third-best-among-regular-starters 96.5 mph with his fastball -- Cole should be able to maintain his 2018 gains, though his ERA might be more variable now that he's more fly ball-oriented. He has exceeded the 200-innings threshold in three of his past four seasons, answering any injury questions from his past, and has excellent odds of being a top-10 fantasy starter for the second consecutive year.

A major league-leading 21 wins and American League-best 1.89 ERA was plenty for Snell to capture Cy Young honors, and the scary part is that his skill set might actually still be improving. A pitcher who before 2018 got plenty of strikeouts with his breaking pitches (curveball and slider) but lacked polished control, Snell lowered his walk rate to 9.1 percent for the season and 7.5 percent after the All-Star break, plus he whiffed 38.5 percent of the batters he faced during the latter time frame. He also reached the 180-innings plateau for the first time as a pro without any sign of late-season fatigue, meaning that the next step might be a 200-inning campaign, with only slight regression in his ERA/WHIP due to unsustainable numbers in terms of left-on-base percentage (88.0) and batting average on balls in play (.242). More volume might balance out any of those possible losses, giving Snell an outstanding chance at yet another top-10 fantasy starter campaign.

Three trips to the disabled list in the past two seasons have cast doubt upon Syndergaard's durability, especially in light of his ordinary 21.8 percent strikeout rate in his healthy final two months of 2018. If you can live with the risk he'll miss time -- or worse, that his past injuries have already taken something away from him -- he still possesses the ability to contend for top-10 starter status. Since Syndergaard's big league debut May 12, 2015, he ranks sixth in ERA (2.93), 14th in strikeout rate (27.1 percent) and 15th in WHIP (1.13) with a minimum of 350 innings. He continues to flash the greatest average fastball velocity among starters (97.5 mph last season), an asset that probably increases his injury risk as much as it makes him a Cy Young contender when healthy. Feelin' lucky?

Bauer opened the door to a possible breakthrough with his 3.01 ERA in the second half of 2017, but he blew that door right off its hinges with a 2018 follow-up that placed him among the top 10 starters in fantasy baseball. That he did so despite a five-week absence due to a fractured fibula makes his performance all the more impressive. As was the case in 2017, Bauer continued to lean more heavily upon his curveball and slider in 2018 (41 percent combined usage) at the expense of his sinker and cutter. He might have a hard time duplicating his 2.21 ERA, but even if he gives back half-to-three-quarters of a run, adding another 5-6 starts to his seasonal total should more than make up the difference. Bauer's star has arrived.

A tale of two seasons: Severino's 2.31 first-half ERA made him a Cy Young candidate, but his 5.57 second-half number made him virtually useless for fantasy purposes, with the minus-3.26 differential the worst decline by any ERA-qualified pitcher in 2018. In fairness, his performance did seem to improve slightly in the season's final weeks, but what was behind his late fade? Poor slider location? Tipping pitches? Opponents becoming more familiar with him? Simple regression? Whatever the cause, Severino's struggles put him on the short list of prominent players to monitor for key improvements during spring training. He has all the skills to rebound, restoring his status as a top-10 starter: Elite fastball velocity, elite command, above-average ground ball rate (when he has full command of his pitches). It's probably smart to bank on a rebound ? but don't say we didn't warn you about keeping an eye on his performance in March.

Injuries have eaten small chunks of Carrasco's four seasons as a full-time member of the Cleveland Indians' rotation, as he has made four trips to the disabled list while averaging 29 starts and 180 innings. But during his healthy periods, he has been one of the most consistently productive starters in fantasy. He has averaged 14 wins, 17 quality starts, a 3.40 ERA, 1.11 WHIP and 206 strikeouts, rarely straying far from those numbers in any individual year. Carrasco has had success thanks to one of the most low-risk skill sets in baseball: He is the only pitcher to make at least 20 starts with at least a 25 percent strikeout and 45 percent ground ball rate with no greater than a 7.5 percent walk rate in each of the past four seasons. Now 32, Carrasco might not have much more room for growth, but keep in mind that he was a top-13 fantasy starter in both Rotisserie and points-based leagues despite three missed weeks in 2018. He's a much safer bet for a similar ranking than you might think.

In another season, Buehler's 2018 stat line might've captured more attention in the Rookie of the Year race, but for some reason, he didn't garner many of the headlines. That is despite the fact that he had many memorable moments, such as his victory in the Los Angeles Dodgers' "Game 163" that earned them the National League West title. Almost every one of his underlying skills metrics was extraordinary: 27.9 percent strikeout rate, 6.8 percent walk rate, 50.7 ground ball rate, 30.8 percent hard-hit rate, with all of those grading much better than league-average. Buehler also didn't sustain an exhausting workload as a rookie, totaling 177 innings between the minors, major-league regular season and postseason, though that did still represent a 79-inning increase over his 2017 number. Even if he's to face adjustments as hitters begin to become more familiar with him, or if he suffers even the slightest amount of fatigue, his skills are too valuable to ignore. If we had the promise of 200-plus innings, Buehler might be a locked in as top-10 starter in all fantasy formats. Yes, he has that much potential.

Injuries have been a huge obstacle in Paxton's path to greatness ? and make no mistake, he has been scraping the surface of greatness for 2 ? years now. Since his permanent recall to the majors on June 1, 2016, he has a 3.52 ERA, 1.16 WHIP and 28.2 percent strikeout rate, the latter two ranking among the 15 best marks in baseball (minimum 250 innings). A significant increase in his average fastball velocity since that date explains much of it, as his 95.8 mph average during that time span is ninth-highest among regular starters. Now with the New York Yankees, Paxton should receive more run and bullpen support, strengthening his statistics, but a uniform change hardly improves his chances of boosting his eight-year, single-season pro best of 171 2/3 innings pitched. Drafting him, which you probably still should amongst the top 20 starters off the board, means accepting the fact that he will almost assuredly have at least one disabled list stint of three-plus weeks.

Considering the obstacles in his path -- a downtick in fastball velocity early, an irregular heartbeat that resurfaced during an August trip to Denver and a pro-career-worst 28.4 percent strikeout rate for the full season -- Jansen's top-50 finish on our Player Rater and near-top-100 fantasy point total were truly extraordinary feats. They were a testament to his immense ability, as was the fact that during the healthiest, most uninterrupted 106-team-games stretch of his season (Apr. 8-Aug. 7), he went 32-of-34 in save chances with a 1.58 ERA and 30.0 percent strikeout rate, which are not a far cry from his annual career averages. Jansen required a second career heart surgery to treat atrial fibrillation, but he's expected to be fine for Opening Day and has spent the winter overhauling his diet, which has resulted in reports of his having lost 25 pounds. He's worth a casual glance during the exhibition season to ensure that his skills are in peak form, but his 2018 shows how good he can be even with limitations: a top-five fantasy closer regardless of format and a candidate for tops at the position if he's back at full strength.

Diaz's 2018 wasn't only indisputably the best among fantasy closers; it was a truly historic campaign among finishers. His 57 saves tied for second-most in a season all time, he became only the seventh pitcher in history with at least 40 saves, a sub-2.0 ERA and a sub-0.80 WHIP season on his r?sum?, and his 44.3 percent strikeout rate was seventh in history by a pitcher with at least 50 innings pitched. Better yet: Diaz converted 27 of 28 save chances with a 1.15 ERA, 0.64 WHIP and 47.9 percent K rate in the Seattle Mariners' final 81 games of 2018, at a time when most might've assumed he'd be more likely to fade after having made 41 appearances in the team's first 81 games. He's bound to regress, as any pitcher coming off a historically excellent season would, and his hefty workload could be a slight issue, but Diaz also gained slightly by the league switch with his winter trade to the New York Mets. He'll close for them, again with some of the best skills of any player at his position. Diaz is well worth being one of the -- if not the -- first closers off your board.

Kimbrel was still seeking a team as spring training camps opened, a strange development considering his career history of historic strikeout totals and the rising number of team strategies utilizing super-'pens. While he still seems likely to find a home in someone's ninth inning, the more time that passes, the greater the odds he could have to settle for either a primary setup role or a team that prefers to mix and match from the bullpen. Kimbrel's shakier-than-usual finish does raise some concerns, as he had a 16.3 percent walk rate, 5.01 ERA and 1.33 WHIP in 31 appearances after the All-Star break (including the postseason), and took his already fly ball-heavy leaning to an even greater extreme. At the same time, he still possesses excellent stuff, owner of two of the three best single seasons in baseball history in terms of strikeout rate (50.2 percent in 2012, 49.6 percent in 2017), and a degree of rebound could be expected in the right circumstances. Kimbrel should still be treated a top-10 fantasy reliever/closer, even as a current free agent.

For a pitcher with this kind of injury history -- eight trips to the disabled list in the past four seasons, resulting in 24-start and 145-inning averages in that time -- Strasburg has been a remarkably productive pitcher around his absences. From 2015 to ?18 among pitchers with at least 50 starts, his 29.5 percent strikeout rate ranked fourth, 2.99 FIP seventh, 1.10 WHIP 11th and 3.27 ERA 15th. Strasburg posted a sub-3 ERA in eight of the 14 months in which he made at least five starts in that same time, which is an unusual level of consistency for a pitcher with his health risk. He's now 30 years old, so improvement -- in performance or the injury department -- probably isn't in the cards, but in this ever-specialized game, his modest workloads are becoming increasingly more valuable, especially in leagues that allow you a maximum of matchups flexibility. Strasburg is a top-10 fantasy talent on a per-game basis, and the prospect of absences shouldn't pull him outside the top 20.

Few pitchers in the game possess as good a slider as Corbin ? his in 2018 was the ninth-best slider in a single year in the 17-year span for which FanGraphs has such data ? and he only improved his chances for success when he added a curveball that got swings and misses nearly 2 percent more often than the league's average. He parlayed that into the majors' third-best FIP (2.47) and fifth-most strikeouts (246), and ultimately a big free-agent payday from the Washington Nationals, where he'll join one of the deepest rotations in the game. Corbin shouldn't suffer in terms of park factors, considering Nationals Park has played similarly over the past five seasons to the humidor-influenced Chase Field in 2018. And though he might have already reached his peak, he's a pretty good bet for another top-15-starter season.

Armed with one of the best sliders in the game -- 85 of his 182 strikeouts came with that pitch, and his 24.2 percent swinging-strike with it was seventh amongst 63 pitchers who threw 500 -- Flaherty was one of last season's most productive rookies in a season full of extraordinary rookie-class production. Remarkably, he wasn't a member of the St. Louis Cardinals' initial rotation, but after being summoned for good on May 15, he never missed a turn and posted a 2.81 ERA and 30.4 percent strikeout rate in his next 23 turns before seemingly fatiguing over his final three starts. Flaherty is now a locked-in member of the team's starting five, and though he might seemed primed for another step forward, keep in mind that he could use some work on his control -- 9.6 percent walk rate in the majors ? and perhaps stamina, having never pitched more than 182 2/3 innings in any of his five professional campaigns. He brings a lot of promise, certainly enough to be a top-25 fantasy starter in all formats, but there might be a hint of rate regression offset by an increase in (big league) workload.

Treinen's strong finish to 2017 -- 12-of-13 in save chances with a 2.51 ERA in the final two months -- carried over nicely into the past season, in which he raised the bar further with the second-best-among-closers fantasy season using either Rotisserie or points-based scoring. Thanks in large part to increased fastball and sinker velocity following his mid-2017 trade to the Oakland Athletics, he posted personal bests in 2018 in strikeout rate (31.8 percent), total strikeouts (100) and FIP (1.82). That's not to mention that he recorded the fourth-best ERA (0.78) of any reliever in history with a minimum of 60 innings pitched. Treinen elevated his ground ball rate during the season's second half to a rate more in range with his days in Washington without giving back any of his swing-and-miss gains, signs that his skill set is that of a locked-in, top-five fantasy closer. If you're going to pay for saves, he's one of the wisest positional investments.

Chapman rebounded from a down 2017, ratcheting his strikeout rate up to 43.9 percent after posting a career-worst 32.9 percent mark the previous campaign. However, Chapman recorded the second-highest walk rate of his career, a bloated 14.2 percent. A below-average BABIP helped keep base runners in check, and he continued to excel at keeping the ball in the yard, allowing only two homers in 51.1 innings. Durability remains an issue, as Chapman failed to reach 60 innings for the fourth time in five seasons, missing a month late in the second half with a sore left knee after dealing with tendinitis in the same knee periodically over the summer. When healthy, Chapman boosts ratios and supplements strikeouts as well as any closer. However, his low save totals in New York reflect missing time as well as the club's willingness to look elsewhere when Chapman's control gets him into trouble.

At a glance, Greinke's 2018 looks like a carbon copy of his 2017, as his ratios were nearly identical and he topped 200 innings for the fourth time in the past five seasons. His strikeout total tumbled, since his rate fell from 26.3 percent to 21.1 percent -- a mark much closer to his previous three-year average. Greinke lost more than a full mile per hour on his average fastball velocity last season, and his slider declined slightly as he generated a 33.2 percent whiff rate with it (44.5 percent in 2017). Now 35, Greinke still has three above-average offerings and good control, which should make his decline a graceful one. Another season with a low-to-mid 3.00s ERA and a sub-1.20 WHIP is attainable, but run support might be a significant issue, as the supporting cast has taken a hit with the departures of Paul Goldschmidt and A.J. Pollock.

Looking at Vazquez's season-ending statistics, it's easy to forget that he avoided a couple of minor scares related to forearm injuries in May. In a pair of separate outings, he allowed four and five runs, and if you choose to exclude those from his seasonal tally -- we, of course, remind that this is generally foolish, with this merely for anecdotal purposes -- he'd have finished with a 1.80 ERA rather than 2.70. That illustrates the variable nature of relief ERAs for those at the top tier of the "most-skilled" list, and the wiser takeaway from Vazquez's season was that he was 21-of-22 in save chances with a 1.72 ERA and 32.0 percent strikeout rate in the Pittsburgh Pirates' final 81 team games. He's a hard-throwing, good-change-of-pace reliever who gets batters out from both sides of the plate, bringing the kind of balance and skills stability to contend for top-five fantasy closer status again in 2019.

In one of last season's more heartwarming stories, Taillon, who endured a lengthy recovery from 2014 Tommy John surgery, then battled testicular cancer in May 2017, set pro-career bests in terms of games started (32), innings pitched (191), wins (14) and strikeouts (179). That was in large part thanks to his significantly ramping up his slider usage, throwing the pitch 25 percent of the time from June 1 forward, an important distinction considering he had 16 quality starts, 12 wins, a 2.63 ERA and a 1.15 WHIP in his final 21 starts of the season. While many might assume he will regress in 2019, considering his track record and inexperience, Taillon might actually have room for growth. He was the No. 22 starting pitcher in both rotisserie and points-based scoring last season, so that's a fair starting point for his draft-day price.

A 75-game suspension for violating MLB's Joint Domestic Violence, Sexual Assault and Child Abuse policy cost Osuna a significant chunk of 2018, though the Houston Astros were nevertheless willing to trade for him around midseason, thrusting him back into a closer's job shortly after his return to eligible status. He went 12-of-14 in save chances with a 1.99 ERA but only a 21.8 percent strikeout rate in 23 appearances following the trade, though he was the Astros' clear choice to close during the season's final weeks, notching 10 of the team's 14 saves from Sept. 1 onward (playoffs included). Osuna has some of the best control of any reliever in baseball -- his 3.9 percent walk rate the past three seasons ranked second among those with 150-plus innings ? and a plus slider that should increase his strikeout rate in 2019. While the Astros tend to mix and match with their bullpen, perhaps cutting into Osuna's number of save chances over a full 162 games, he should be utilized enough to be a potential top-five fantasy closer.

During his year-and-two-fifths second stint with the New York Yankees, Robertson continued to post closer-worthy skills despite being relegated to setup relief. His 2.49 ERA during that span was 23rd among relievers (minimum 60 innings), his 0.94 WHIP sixth and his 34.2 percent strikeout rate 11th, and he posted sub-.260 wOBA against both sides, including limiting left-handed hitters to a .255 mark with a 41.1 percent strikeout rate. Now with the Philadelphia Phillies, Robertson shapes up as the team's go-to option in the ninth inning, meaning the saves to go with those sterling ratios should place him among the 10 best fantasy closers for 2019. Yes, Phillies manager Gabe Kapler does like to mix and match with his bullpen, so Robertson might not get every save chance, but the right-hander is easily his top talent and should earn the team's runaway lead in the category.

A midseason trade to the Cleveland Indians, who mixed and matched with him and Cody Allen in the ninth inning during the season's final two months, might've been the only thing standing in Hand's path to a top-five fantasy closer performance in 2018. He whiffed at least 30 percent of the hitters he faced for the third consecutive year, with his 35.2 percent rate in 2018 setting a new personal best, and he seemed to regress only against right-handed hitters (.322 wOBA) due to a bloated .320 BABIP against them. Hand has established himself as one of the most talented relievers in the game, and despite his left-handedness, he's the favorite for saves with the Cleveland Indians entering this year following Allen's free-agent departure. Expect more situational tinkering, which will limit Hand's save total, but he should still get enough opportunities to be a top-10 fantasy option at the position.

Are Bumgarner's skills truly in decline, or are a pair of entirely fluky injuries that cost him more than 40 percent of the San Francisco Giants' schedule the past two seasons more to blame? He suffered bruised ribs and a shoulder sprain as a result of a dirt bike accident in April 2017, then a fractured left pinky finger when he was struck by a batted ball during a March 2018 exhibition game -- things that aren't exactly related to in-game wear and tear. Bumgarner's strikeout rate in the 38 big league starts he made around those absences did plummet, however, slipping to a troubling 19.8 percent last season, and he has posted the lowest average fastball velocities (among full big league years) in those two campaigns. He'll need to look rather sharp come spring training to expect a return to the near-Cy Young levels he has exhibited in the past, but with likely greater luck in the health department, he could be a top-30 fantasy starting pitcher in 2019.

Foltynewicz leapt into the top-20 fantasy starters in both Rotisserie and points-based scoring leagues last season, thanks in large part to greater usage and performance of his slider as well as a noticeable increase in his average fastball velocity. He threw his slider roughly 6 percent more often, and FanGraphs had it a top-six pitch among ERA qualifiers. Additionally, his 96.3 mph average fastball velocity was third-highest among regular starters. Still, Foltynewicz enjoyed a bit of good fortune, particularly his .252 batting average allowed on balls in play (third-lowest among ERA qualifiers), so there's bound to be some correction to his ratios. He has made great strides in his career, however, establishing himself as a clear front-of-a-staff starter. Expect him to finish at the very least within range of his 2018 season-ending numbers in his follow-up attempt.

Clevinger's breaking pitches -- curveball and slider -- rank among the best in the game, as FanGraphs had them worth a combined 18.8 runs above average, and our own pitch-tracking tool had him posting a .197 wOBA and 19.2 percent swinging-strike rate with the two pitches, with both of those rating among the game's top 25 percent. Clevinger rode those to a breakthrough campaign in 2018, lowering his walk rate and FIP for the second consecutive year and posting 21 quality starts, seventh-most in baseball. Perhaps better yet: Clevinger was 10-of-13 in quality starts with a 2.31 ERA, 1.03 WHIP and 28.6 percent strikeout rate after the All-Star break, and he gave the Cleveland Indians their best start in their three-game exit from the American League Division Series. He's a budding ace and should be regarded as a borderline top-20 fantasy starting pitcher with the improvements he has made.

Re-signed to a three-year extension to serve as the Cincinnati Reds' closer, Iglesias should be one of the more reliable choices in fantasy at his position, a bona fide top-10 candidate among finishers regardless of format. He has posted at least a 25 percent strikeout rate each of the past three seasons, coinciding with his permanent move to the bullpen, and is one of the harder-working closers in the game, having made 51 appearances of at least four outs the past three seasons combined. Iglesias did, however, post an unusually high FIP last season (4.23), driven in large part by his allowing 12 home runs in 72 innings' work, and while that puts him at risk for the occasional ugly outing, it was driven by an unusually high home run/fly ball percentage (13.3 percent, up from 10.1 percent for his career).

While Price's playoff heroics got rid of some of the narrative surrounding him, it didn't get rid of the tear in his elbow. He's proven he can be quite effective; just keep in mind there's still an injury risk. In addition, playoff heroes often incur a ranking bump from recency bias. Last season's 3.58 ERA was light according to the sabermetric ERA estimators, suggesting a correction toward 4.00. In addition, he maintained the same strikeout rate as the previous couple of campaigns, despite a marked drop in swinging-strike rate. If Price doesn't revert, he could see a reduction in strikeouts. To help mitigate these potential issues, Price can reduce homers allowed, as he posted a high 13.2 percent HR/FB last season. Price is still a front-end fantasy starter, but he comes with more risk than last October may suggest.

Hader's 2018 was a season for the ages: He whiffed a major-league-leading 46.7 percent of the batters he faced, the fourth-best rate by any pitcher with at least 50 innings pitched in a single season in history, and he had 18 appearances of at least two innings pitched without allowing a run, the most by any pitcher in six years. Such a performance will be practically impossible to repeat, especially since he pitched a combined 91 1/3 innings in the regular season and postseason and therefore could be at risk of fatigue. However, if he's able to at all lower his 9.8 percent walk rate, he could run away with the Milwaukee Brewers' closer role and be the unquestioned No. 1 reliever in fantasy. As is, Hader finished fifth on the Player Rater and in fantasy points among all relief pitchers in 2018, despite only 12 saves. His value will be greatest in leagues that allow daily transactions, as he can be slotted in around your starters while maximizing his amazing ratios.

Berrios continued to show steady skills growth in big league year No. 3 in 2018, improving his strikeout, walk and ground-ball rates again after having also done so in 2017, resulting in the majors' 18th-best ERA qualified K rate (25.4 percent). Perhaps most important, he totaled 32 starts and 192 1/3 innings pitched, and while he did struggle to the tune of a 4.56 ERA in his final 10 turns, it was a big plus in terms of improving his stamina. Berrios continues to flash solid performance with both his fastball and curveball, so another step forward in 2019 isn't entirely unthinkable. He was a top-30 fantasy starting pitcher, regardless of format last season, and has good odds of being the same again this year.

On a per-inning basis, Doolittle was one of the most effective relievers in baseball last season, as he carried a 10.0 K/BB while posting career-best ERA (1.60) and WHIP (0.60) marks over 45 frames. Durability has been an issue for Doolittle, but fortunately, he did not miss time with shoulder trouble in 2018 after he required DL stints for strains and a torn rotator cuff from 2015-2017. He was able to return from a toe injury suffered in July before the end of the regular season. Despite losing a tick on his fastball, Doolittle generated more whiffs with the pitch last season, throwing it 88.5 percent of the time while mixing in the occasional slider or splitter. He'll open 2019 as the Nationals' closer and should remain in that role as long as he's healthy, but it would be foolish to expect much more than 50 innings from him, as he's only reached that number once in the past four seasons.

Giles' hold on the closer role in Houston seemed tenuous at the beginning of the 2018 season, as he lost the trust of manager A.J. Hinch during the team's 2017 World Series triumph over the Dodgers. After he had posted back-to-back seasons with an elite strikeout rate, Giles' rate dropped to 25 percent in 2018, but he offset the missing whiffs by reducing his walk rate to a career-low 3.3 percent (career 7.4 percent). His inconsistency and an on-field verbal blow-up when Hinch removed him from a game in July prompted the Astros to send Giles to Toronto when they acquired Roberto Osuna from the Blue Jays. Giles' ratios improved after the trade, but his home-run rate spiked (1.83 HR/9). Giles still has an elite slider, which he used to generate a 51.2 percent whiff rate last season, but the effectiveness of his fastball waned with a slight drop in velocity (98.2 to 97.3 mph). He should have every opportunity to lock down the ninth-inning role for the Jays this season, and if he can improve his fastball command and reduce his home run rate, Giles still has a shot to be a top-10 closer.

Davis racked up 43 saves during his first season with the Rockies, working through a reduced strikeout rate (10.7 K/9) by slightly improving his walk rate (3.6 BB/9) and reaping the benefits of a career-low BABIP (.238). Without an elite strikeout rate, Davis' margin for error is slimmer than that of most, but his ERA (4.13) was nearly a half run higher than his FIP (3.65) thanks to a surprisingly low strand rate (66.9 percent, his lowest mark as a full-time reliever). The selling point with Davis comes from his job security, as the Rockies rarely asked him to get more than three outs at a time and seem content to use him as a traditional closer with $36 million remaining on his contract over the next two seasons. Tread carefully, as his decline might be accelerated by Coors Field as his velocity continues to wane.

October Tommy John surgery will preclude him from pitching this season, but because he's so adept with the bat, he's more than capable of handling everyday designated hitter duties for the Los Angeles Angels, if they so wish. He might not be ready to play until several weeks into the season, but once healthy, he's a legitimately elite power source, having posted the majors' eighth-best isolated power (.279) and 10th-best hard contact rate (50.2 percent) amongst hitters with at least 350 plate appearances. Ohtani's 27.8 percent strikeout rate is a bit of a concern in terms of repeating his lofty batting average, and his .222/.300/.354 triple-slash line against left-handed pitchers could be a further concern if he's a true regular, but all the chatter about his hitting when he came over from Japan seems entirely valid (if not understated). As for those of you wondering about his pitching prospects in dynasty/keeper leagues, we'll see. The Angels plan on a bright future for him in their rotation, and he sure looked like an ace in the 10 starts he made, but he will once again face injury and workload questions entering 2020.

Of course, the preponderance of homers Tanaka surrenders is undesirable, but he's stingy with walks and gets a generous number of whiffs, helping to soften the impact. That said, there's a latent trend in terms of innings pitched, as he has gone from an average of 6.44 innings pitched per start in 2016, to 5.94 in 2017, to 5.78 last season. Some of that may be due to the Yankees building an uber-bullpen, but it's also because Tanaka gives up a high percentage of his homers the third time through the order. Homers are so variable, especially in Yankee Stadium, and with a few more, we're looking at a league-average ERA. A few less, and we have a borderline ace. As alluded to, Tanaka's career 23.9 strikeout and 4.8 walk rates provide a solid fantasy floor with a solid WHIP and strikeout total. An aggressive ranking on Tanaka is a bet he keeps the ball in the yard.

After he was the breakthrough fantasy closer of 2017, Knebel's 2018 was cast off track just three appearances in when he suffered a hamstring strain while delivering a pitch. He couldn't recapture the magic upon his return, posting a 3.91 first-half ERA and ultimately slipping into a season-long timeshare that at times included both Josh Hader and Jeremy Jeffress. Once demoted into lower-pressure situations in September, Knebel appeared recharged, finishing the year with a 0.34 ERA and 52.2 percent strikeout rate in his final 25 appearances (playoffs included). With the strong finish, he's as good a bet to close for the Brewers in 2019 as either Hader or Jeffress, and the uncertainty about the team's plans could make him a potential bargain. Consider Knebel the favorite in that race, and he's worthy of a speculative top-20 pick at his position.
